{It may seem that preparing and carrying out ...d6-d5 is simpler than ...b6-b5
as examined in the previous article. Black can coordinate many of his pieces
to control d5 and advance the central pawn under normal circumstances whereas
with ...b6-b5 certain tactical premises are needed in most cases. But the
problem is that ...d6-d5 opens the position in an area of high interest for
both sides, namely the center. White may have many of his pieces playing a
part in the initiated fight as well, so things can turn tactical here, too. On
top, the pawn contact is also more complex than after ...b6-b5. In principle,
if White does not have enough resources to simply win the d-pawn with a double
capture on d5, his main chance for retaining an advantage is e4-e5. This is an
important issue as he typically needs to keep an indirect control on e5 (for
instance by doubling major pieces on the e-file). We know already that playing
f2-f4 is double-edged, as after ...g7-g6 Black would threaten ...e6-e5, a pawn
break examined in the next article. In the first example, White seemed to be
well prepared against the central break, but he overlooked a subtle tactical
detail:} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Qxd4 Bb7 7. Bg2
d6 8. O-O Be7 9. e4 O-O 10. Qe3 {N} a6 11. Nd4 Qc7 12. b3 Nbd7 13. Bb2 {
Uhlmann designed this system of developing right from the early days of the
Hedgehog's burst of popularity. He continued playing it for decades, obtaining
excellent results with it, but against the Romanian hedgehog specialists
Gheorghiu and Suba he failed to control the position in the desired way.} Rfe8
$1 14. h3 $5 Bf8 15. Rae1 Nc5 16. Kh2 Rad8 $1 17. Re2 $5 g6 18. Nc2 {Preparing
f2-f4 without running into ...e6-e5, but removing the knight from the center
offers Black additional ideas.} ({The neutral} 18. Rfe1 $5 {may have been
better.}) 18... Bg7 {Black suddenly threatens ...Nfxe4! using the long
diagonal weakening caused by the previous move.} 19. Ba1 {[#]Both sides have
regrouped thoroughly, but Black's coordination is more effective. The f1-rook
is not in the game yet and the dark-squared bishop went back to an unnatural
square in order to avoid tactical tricks based on ...Nxe4. Black cannot
improve his piece position anymore which makes the next move not only logical
but also a necessity.} d5 $1 20. e5 Nfd7 21. cxd5 {The crucial move order.} ({
If} 21. f4 {then} dxc4 $15 {when White is left with weaknesses.}) 21... Nxe5
22. f4 {[#]White must have put big hopes in this move. It seems that Black
simply loses material. But his perfect coordination also implies a high
dynamic potential which allows the following small combination:} exd5 $1 $15 {
A nasty trick based on Black's superior coordination.} (22... Ned3 $2 {and 22..
.Ned7 both lose a piece to} 23. b4 $16) 23. fxe5 d4 $1 ({After the knight
retreat to c2 the advance of the d-pawn is an obvious issue in the spirit of
Nimzowitsch's theory about the blockade. But there is an alternate move order
to achieve that:} 23... Rxe5 {may also result in a draw, the same as the game
continuation, but it requires less imagination from White:} 24. Qd2 d4 25. Rxe5
Bxe5 26. Ne2 Bxg2 27. Kxg2 Ne4 (27... d3 28. Bxe5 Qxe5 29. Nc3 $14 {offers
White chances.}) 28. Qd3 Nc5 $11 {with a perpetual repetition.}) 24. Nxd4 Rxe5
25. Qf2 {[#]} Nd3 $1 ({Black does not fall into the elegant trap:} 25... Rxd4
$2 26. Nb5 $1 $16 axb5 27. Qxd4 {with a decisive pin along the a1-h8 diagonal.
(Gheorghiu)}) 26. Qg1 $2 ({Confronted with unexpected problems Uhlmann fails
to find the following line indicated by Gheorghiu:} 26. Qxf7+ $1 Qxf7 27. Rxf7
Kxf7 28. Bxb7 Rxd4 29. Ne4 $1 Rdxe4 30. Rxe4 $1 (30. Bxe4 $2 Rxe4 31. Rxe4 Bxa1
$17) 30... Rxe4 (30... Ra5 31. Bxg7 Rxa2+ 32. Kg1 Kxg7 33. Re6 $11 {does not
change anything - Marin}) 31. Bxe4 $11 {Quite an accurate and honest comment
by Gheorghiu!}) 26... Rxd4 $1 $17 {Black retrieves the piece and keeps the
extra pawn that he won along the way.} 27. Rd2 (27. Qxd4 Rxe2 28. Qxg7+ {
does not work:} Kxg7 29. Nd5+ Kh6 30. Nxc7 Rxg2+ 31. Kh1 Nf2+ {wins the
exchange. Of course, Black could first win the g3- and a2-pawn before playing .
.Nf2+, but this would not make much of a difference.}) 27... Bxg2 28. Qxg2 Re3
{[#]Black is a pawn up and has an overwhelming domination.} 29. Rf3 Rxf3 30.
Qxf3 Qd8 $1 31. Qe3 Rd7 32. Re2 h6 33. Qg1 Ne5 $19 34. Qg2 Rd3 35. Rf2 Qd4 $1
36. Bb2 Rxc3 37. Bxc3 Qxc3 38. Qa8+ Kh7 39. Qxa6 Qe3 40. Qe2 Qc5 41. Rf1 h5 42.
Qe4 b5 43. Re1 $2 Qf2+ 0-1

