{One important element in Black's counterplay launched with ...d6-d5 is to
clear the h2-b8 and a3-f8 diagonals for the queen and bishop respectively.
These aspects must have been underestimated by the strong player with white in
the following game.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O
Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. Rd1 a6 10. b3 Nbd7 11. e4 Qb8 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Nd2
Rd8 14. a4 Qc7 15. Qe3 Rac8 16. Qe2 Ne5 $5 {An original move, inducing White
weakening his kingside.} ({As we know from the previous article, the typical
reaction after a2-a4 is.} 16... Nc5) 17. h3 {Preparing to push back the
irritating knight with f2-f4.} h5 $1 {The plan employed by Black in this game
caused some sensation in the epoque, not least because of the result and the
big rating difference between the opponents. Black intends to weaken White's
dark squares with ...h5-h4.} 18. f4 Ng6 19. Nf3 {[#]} d5 $1 ({More ambitious
than} 19... h4 20. Nxh4 (20. f5 exf5 21. exf5 $11 {Ftacnik}) 20... Nxh4 21.
gxh4 g6 22. Bf3 d5 23. e5 Ne4 24. Nxe4 dxe4 25. Bxe4 Bxe4 26. Qxe4 b5 $44 {
Black has enough compensation for the pawns but this should suffice for a draw
only.}) 20. cxd5 $6 {This allows Black additional ideas.} (20. e5 $6 {leaves
the kingside exposed.} Ne4 21. Nxe4 dxe4 22. Nd4 (22. Nd2 Rd3 $1 $17 {attacks
b3 and g3}) 22... h4 23. Bxe4 hxg3 $1 24. Bxg6 ({A desperate counterattack.} 
24. Bxb7 Qxb7 $17 {followed by ...Nh4 and ...Bc5 endangers the white king
while also retaining the better structure.}) 24... fxg6 25. Qg4 Bc5 $1 {
The start of the decisive attack involving almost all of Black's pieces.} 26.
Qxe6+ (26. Qxg3 Qc6 27. Kh2 Qe4 28. Re1 Rxd4 $1 29. Rxe4 Rd2+ {wins}) 26... Kh7
27. f5 gxf5 $1 28. Qxf5+ Kg8 29. Qg5 Qc6 30. Qxg3 Qe4 $19 {White cannot defend
his knight and king at the same time (lines indicated by Ftacnik).}) ({The
most restrictive move order is} 20. exd5 $5 exd5 ({One important point is that
the same idea as in the game} 20... h4 $6 {runs into} 21. Ne5 $1) 21. Nxd5 Nxd5
22. cxd5 Bxd5 $15 {when Black has only the more pleasant position.}) {[#]}
20... h4 $3 {After this well-timed pawn break White's kingside collapses.} (
20... exd5 21. Nxd5 {transposes above.}) 21. Nxh4 {Ftacnik analyses a series
of alternatives, but none of them saves White.} (21. Ng5 hxg3 $1 22. dxe6 Qc5+
23. Kh1 Nxf4 24. exf7+ Kh8 $19 {White's counterattack has come to an end and
he is hanging all over the board.}) (21. e5 Bc5+ 22. Kh1 (22. Nd4 Nxd5 $17 {
once again leaves White with problems on g3, f4 and d4.}) 22... Nh5 23. Ne4 {
Ftacnik now analyses only} Bxd5 24. Rxd5 $1 exd5 25. Nfg5 $13 {but 23...Rxd5!
keeping the bishop is stronger, dooming White's kingside.}) ({Or if} 21. dxe6
Bc5+ 22. Kh1 Nh5 23. exf7+ {Black can improve over Ftacnik's analysis with} Kh8
$19 {followed by the knights' invasion.}) ({With the e-file obstructed} 21. Ne5
{does not make sense.} Nxe5 22. fxe5 Bc5+ 23. Kh1 Qxe5 $19 {In all these lines,
Black frequently uses the dark diagonals cleared by his d-pawn.}) {[#]} 21...
Nxh4 22. gxh4 Qxf4 $17 {Black has a very active play and the better structure
while the white king is vulnerable. This is more important than the (most
likely temporarily) missing pawn.} 23. dxe6 fxe6 24. e5 $6 Bc5+ 25. Kh1 Nh5 $1
26. Qxh5 Qg3 27. Nd5 ({A desperate move trying to avoid mate as after, for
instance} 27. Qg4 Bxg2#) ({or} 27. Qe2 Qxh3#) 27... Rxd5 28. Rf1 {[#]The last
hope: White threatens with a draw by perpetual after 29.Qf7+ Kh8 30.Qh5+. But
Black can finish off things quickly:} Qxg2+ $1 29. Kxg2 Rd2+ 30. Kg3 Rg2+ 31.
Kf4 Rf8+ {and mate on the next move.} 0-1

