{In the previous examples, the consequences of the central break depended on
concrete and sometimes tactical play. But there are cases when the struggle
does not finish so quickly and ...d6-d5 leads to a long strategical struggle.
Here is a good example on this theme:} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 c5 3. Nf3 e6 4. g3 b6
5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. Rd1 a6 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Qd2 O-O
12. Bf4 Ne8 13. Rac1 Qc7 14. e4 Rd8 15. Qe2 Nef6 16. Nd2 Rfe8 17. h3 Qb8 18. b4
{[#]Due to White's move order, Black has reached a harmonious regrouping not
without efforts and losing time. White has prepared an ambitious plan based on
Nb3 and c4-c5 using the bishop's placement on f4 and the time wasted by
Black's king's knight. With his next move Black burns his bridges and goes
straight for ...d6-d5.} Qa8 ({His decision is correct but actually he could
have also chosen the slow mode with} 18... Bf8 19. Nb3 Rc8) 19. Nb3 d5 $1 ({
Defending d6 with} 19... Ne5 $2 {does not work due to} 20. c5 $16) 20. e5 $1 ({
The only challenging answer as after} 20. cxd5 exd5 21. exd5 {or 21.e5 Black
has} Bxb4 $15) 20... Ne4 {[#]After the initial clash things remain unclear in
the center and both sides need to act with care.} 21. cxd5 {This has the merit
of forcing Black to exchange his active knight.} ({Carrying out the exchange
himself with} 21. Nxe4 dxe4 {would offer Black counterplay with simple moves:}
22. a3 ({Black manages to stabilize after} 22. c5 bxc5 23. bxc5 Bd5 $11) 22...
e3 $5 23. f3 (23. Bxb7 exf2+ {is even preferable for Black due to his better
structure while}) (23. fxe3 $2 {loses a piece to} g5) 23... a5 {and White has
problems to control the play on both wings.}) 21... Nxc3 $1 (21... exd5 $2 {
leaves the e6-square poorly defended allowing} 22. e6 $1 $16 {for instance}
fxe6 23. Nxe4 dxe4 24. Bc7 {winning an exchange.}) 22. Rxc3 {[#]} Nf8 $3 {
A fantastic move preparing to capture on d5 with pieces. If ...exd5 would be
necessary anyway then the knight could be installed on the perfect blocking
square e6. In his comments for the Chess Informant, Ftacnik explains why he
refrained from concrete action:} (22... Bxb4 $2 23. Rc7 Bxd5 24. Bxd5 exd5 25.
Qg4 {leaves the b4-bishop exposed to Bh6 or Bg5.}) (22... Bxd5 23. Bxd5 exd5
24. a3 $16 {is given by Ftacnik without further explanation. The point is that
Black is too slow to reach the desired regrouping:} Nf8 25. Nd4 Ne6 26. Nxe6
fxe6 27. Qg4 Bf8 28. Rdc1 $16 {and the weakness on e6 prevents Black from
fighting for the c-file.}) 23. b5 $1 {White, too, is at the height of the
situation. Since 23...a5 24.Nc6 ensures the invasion on c6, Black is forced to
allow the opening of a new front.} (23. a3 {would most likely lead to a draw:}
Bxd5 24. Bxd5 Rxd5 25. Rxd5 Qxd5 26. Qxa6 Ra8 $11 {[%csl Ga3] Ftacnik.}) ({
Ftacnik also analyses the following interesting line:} 23. d6 $5 Bxg2 24. f3
Bxh3 25. Kh2 ({I would add that} 25. dxe7 {is premature since} Rxd1+ {comes
with check, not allowing the knight capture.} 26. Qxd1 Ng6 {with complicated
play}) 25... Bxd6 $1 ({But now Black has to be careful:} 25... Bf5 $2 26. dxe7
$1 Rxe7 27. Rxd8 Qxd8 28. Bg5 $14) 26. exd6 e5 $1 {with counterplay.}) 23...
axb5 24. Qxb5 Bxd5 25. Bxd5 Rxd5 26. Rxd5 exd5 {[#]White's position is
somewhat more active but this tends to be temporary. The d5-pawn is very
strong and the knight will stand wonderfully on e6.} 27. Be3 (27. Qxb6 Qxa2 $11
{is most likely leading to a draw.}) ({With the modified queenside structure,} 
27. Nd4 $2 {does not work out at all due to} Bc5 $1 {This resource was not
available in the line above.} 28. Nf5 d4 {followed by ...Ne6 and Black already
has the initiative. The game move aims to keep Black busy with defending his
b-pawn.}) 27... Bc5 $1 {Another brilliant move. Black does not need the bishop
nor the b6-pawn for the blockade, so he gives them away in order to clear the
knight's path to e6.} 28. Nxc5 {This is the only chance to continue fighting
for an advantage but strategically it is dangerous to keep the bishop against
a perfect black knight.} ({Boensch probably rejected} 28. Bxc5 bxc5 29. Rxc5
Rxe5 {because it leaves the e-file undefended offering Black enough
counterplay, for instance:} 30. a4 Re1+ 31. Kh2 Rb1 32. Rxd5 Rb2 33. Kg2 (33.
Rd2 Rb1 $1 $11 {forces a move repetition.}) 33... g6 $11 {followed by ...Ne6
when White cannot defend his king and promote his pawn at the same time.})
28... bxc5 {In the resulting structure, the knight will be very versatile and
will eventually prove stronger than the bishop.} 29. Rxc5 {Hoping for 29...
Rxe5 30.a4+/- when, unlike in the previous line, Black has no counterplay
along the e-file.} ({If} 29. Bxc5 Rb8 $1 {White should probably give up the
a2-pawn (and the hopes to win) with 30.Qd3 since} 30. Qe2 d4 {offers Black
enormous counterplay:} 31. Rb3 Ne6 32. Bd6 Rxb3 33. axb3 {With queens on the
board and such a strong knight, the kingside weaknesses offer no hope for a
win if Black simply stands still. But he can also start a dangerous attack with
} Ng5 {for instance} 34. f4 $6 Ne4 35. Qd3 Qa1+ 36. Kg2 Qe1 $15) {[#]} 29... d4
$1 {Black starts his counterplay based on small tactical nuances allowed by
the knight's superior versatility over the bishop.} 30. Bc1 (30. Bxd4 Ne6 {
wins material:} 31. Rc4 Rd8 ({Ftacnik's} 31... Rb8 $2 {actually loses after
the unexpected} 32. Ra4 $1) 32. Qa4 Qxa4 33. Rxa4 Nxd4) ({But} 30. Bd2 {
looks more natural.}) 30... Rb8 31. Qd3 Qxa2 32. Qxd4 {Forced as the position
with equal pawns after ...Ne6 would obviously favor Black.} Ne6 {[#]} 33. Qc4
$6 {A first inaccuracy. White probably overlooked the elegant queen retreat.} (
33. Qd5 Qe2 34. Rc6 $1 h6 {(Ftacnik) offers Black enough compensation, but
White should hold.}) 33... Qa8 $1 {White now needs big efforts to defend the
long diagonal and the back rank.} 34. Rc6 Nd4 35. Rc5 $2 ({In time trouble it
is not easy to discern between the real and apparent threats. As dangerous as
they may seem,} 35. Ra6 Qe4 36. Qc7) ({or} 35. Rd6 Nf3+ (35... Rc8 36. Rxd4
Rxc4 37. Rxc4 {should also lead to a draw.}) 36. Kg2 Nh4+ 37. Kf1 Qg2+ 38. Ke2
{do does not offer Black more than a perpetual.}) 35... Rd8 36. Be3 $2 Nf3+ 37.
Kf1 Nh2+ 38. Ke1 Qh1+ {and mate on the next move. A dramatic game and quite an
instructive one in all its phases.} 0-1

