{[#]Is Black prepared for} 19... d5 {Actually not.} 20. cxd5 ({Good enough but
} 20. e5 $1 {is at least as strong.} Ne4 21. Nxe4 dxe4 22. Nxe6 $1 {This is
not hard to see but White probably could not evaluate the ultimate
consequences of the next move correctly.} e3 23. Qxd7 Bxg2 24. Nxf8 Bxh3 25.
Rc2 Rcd8 (25... Qf3 26. Nxh7 $3 {this move indirectly defends g4 and saves the
knight.} Kxh7 27. Qxf7+ {mates.}) 26. Bxd8 Rxd8 {Retreating with the queen
would allow ...Rd2 winning but...} 27. Rxe3 $1 Kxf8 28. e6 $1 Rxd7 (28... fxe6
29. Qxe6 Rd1+ 30. Re1 {parries all threats.}) 29. exd7 Bxg4 30. Re8+ Qxe8 31.
dxe8=Q+ Kxe8 32. c5 {with a probable win.}) 20... exd5 21. e5 Ne4 22. Nxe4 Rxc1
23. Rxc1 dxe4 24. Bf2 $2 ({Even now White should play against the hanging
knight:} 24. Nf5 $1 {But once again things were not easy to foresee tactically:
} Nc5 (24... e3 25. Qxd7 Bxg2 26. e6 Rxe6 27. Rc7 Qe8 28. Nh6+ Bxh6 29. Rc8 $18
) 25. Nd6 Bxd6 26. exd6 e3 27. Qe2 Bxg2 28. Qxg2 Qxg2+ 29. Kxg2 e2 30. b4 Nd7
31. Be7 $16) 24... Nc5 $17 {Black has a dream position already and went on to
win the game.} 0-1

