{[#]How did Black justify his central break after} 19... d5 20. exd5 Nf4 $1 $17
{An original way of making use of the control over the h2-b8 diagonal.} 21.
Nde2 (21. Bf3 Ncd3 {gives Black the decisive initiative.}) 21... Nxg2 22. Kxg2
exd5 (22... b5 $1 {shaking White's stability was even stronger.}) 23. cxd5 (23.
Nxd5 Ne4 24. Qf4 Nxg5 $15) 23... Rcd8 (23... b5 $5 24. b4 Nd7) 24. Qf4 Bd6 {
In the absence of the g2-bishop, and with the king's position strongly
weakened, White faces serious problems despite his extra pawn.} 25. Qg4 Be5 26.
Kg1 a5 27. Rd2 Bc8 28. Qf3 b5 29. h4 b4 30. Nd1 Ne4 31. Rd3 Ba6 32. Re3 Nd2 33.
Qh3 Bxb2 34. Nxb2 Bxe2 35. Rxe8+ Rxe8 0-1

