{The pawn breaks examined in the previous two articles (...b6-b5 and ...d6-d5)
are mainly aimed at questioning White's stability on the light squares. Since
White's central space advantage is ensured by the c4- and e4-pawns we may call
these the main pawn break plans. Additionally, Black disposes of over ...e6-e5,
which we can consider as an auxiliary break. The usually favorable
circumstances for Black are with the g-pawn on g6 (or else with Nd4-f5
inoffensive) and the white pawn on f4, in order to clear the e5-square for the
black pieces or else provoke the opening of the e-file with increased pressure
on e4. Sometimes, ...e6-e5 can prove effective even with the pawn on f2, as
driving the knight away from d4 would make ...b6-b5 easier to carry out. And
of course, it would help if White has played g3-g4, chronically weakening the
e5-square. If White plays h2-h3 Black can sometimes try combining ...e6-e5
with ... h5-h4, gaining the control over f4. All these aspects make us
understand that the potential danger of the break on dark squares tends to
inhibit the active plan based on f2-f4, or at least, provoke the willingly
knight retreat from d4. We had this situation in the previous articles, but
now we will examine games in which this pawn break came true. In the first
game we will see that in such cases not all that glitters is gold actually.} 1.
c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6
9. e4 Nbd7 10. Qe3 Be7 11. Nd4 Qc7 12. b3 O-O 13. Bb2 Rfe8 14. Kh1 Bf8 15. f4
g6 16. Rae1 Bg7 17. h3 Rad8 {[#]In the article focusing on ...d6-d5, I have
mentioned that this system was popularized by Uhlmann. We have already seen
how he lost to Gheorghiu, now he will fall victim to another leading Romanian
grandmaster.} 18. g4 {The idea behind this move is not very clear, as after 19.
g5 Nh5 Black would exercise unpleasant pressure against f4 and g3.} ({It is
true, however, that White does not have obvious ways of developing his
initiative, for instance} 18. e5 $2 dxe5 19. fxe5 Bxg2+ 20. Kxg2 Qxe5 $1 {
(Suba) and the d4-knight is hanging.}) ({Removing the knight from the center
with} 18. Nc2 {does not work as a preparation for e4-e5, for instance:} b5 $1 {
(The c2-knight is hanging)} 19. e5 $2 Bxg2+ 20. Kxg2 dxe5 21. fxe5 Nxe5 $17 22.
Qxe5 $2 Rd2+ 23. Rf2 $2 Rxf2+ 24. Kxf2 Ng4+ $1 $19 {wins the queen.}) {[#]}
18... e5 $6 {This thematical move is premature and gives meaning to White's
previous move.} ({The best way to prepare for the central break was} 18... Nc5
{Black increases his pressure against e4 before opening the e-file at the cost
of weakening the d5 square.} 19. Ba1 {Trying to avoid a pin along the long
diagonal and avoiding a later double attack against d3.} (19. e5 {still does
not work due to} dxe5 20. fxe5 Nfd7 $17 {which collects the e5-pawn as} 21. b4
Nxe5 22. bxc5 Nxc4 $19 {retrieves the piece and keeps the extra pawns.}) (19.
Rd1 {avoids the tactical threats but offers Black pleasant play on the dark
squares and along the e-file after} e5 20. fxe5 Rxe5 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. cxd5 Rde8
) 19... e5 20. Nde2 (20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Nc2 Rd3 $17 {followed by ...Rxc3 and ...
Nfxe4 with a strong initiative for the exchange.}) 20... exf4 21. Nxf4 Qd7 {
planning ...b5 to endanger the e4-pawn..}) (18... h6 $5 {[%cal Ge6e5] would be
the second best way of preparing ...e6-e5. Since after the central break one
of White's ideas will be to weaken Black's control over d5 with g4-g5, it is
best to take preventive measures.}) 19. fxe5 Rxe5 ({The natural} 19... Nxe5 {
is somewhat better. True, White retains his space advantage even though Black
remains stable.} 20. Qd2 Rc8 21. Nd5 Qd8 22. a4 $14) {[#]} 20. Nde2 $6 {
After this neutral move, planning to prepare g4-g5 with Ng3, Black gets
entirely satisfactory counterplay.} ({The critical move was:} 20. g5 $1 Nh5 21.
Nd5 {The main point is that the only way to capture is} Bxd5 22. cxd5 $14 {
[%cal Gd4c6] allowing a later Nc6, while Bf3 is also an unpleasant threat.})
20... Rde8 21. Ng3 h6 $1 {Better late than never.} 22. Qd2 R5e7 23. Re3 Ne5 {
An indirect way of preparing against Nd5.} ({The discussion whether in such
situations} 23... Nc5 $5 {would be better is initiated in the next examples.})
{[#]} 24. Ba3 $2 {White starts to lose the thread. Black is forced to defend
d6, but the next move restores the communication between the wings.} ({He
probably refrained from} 24. Nd5 {due to} Nxd5 25. exd5 Nxg4 $5 26. Rxe7 Qxe7 {
but things are not entirely clear here:} 27. Bxg7 Kxg7 28. Qd4+ (28. hxg4 $2
Qh4+ $17) 28... Ne5 29. Qxb6 $132 {It is not clear yet whose majority is more
dangerous.}) 24... Rd7 25. Re2 Rc8 {This slows down a bit the rhythm of the
initiative. The rook was well placed on e8.} (25... b5 $1 {is one of the best
two ways of taking over the initiative, combining threats on both wings.} 26.
cxb5 axb5 27. Nxb5 Qd8 $1 {Taking full advantage of the merits behind ...Rd7.}
28. Bb2 (28. g5 hxg5 29. Qxg5 {allows a series of tactical blows:} Ba6 30. Nc3
Nh5 $1 31. Qe3 Nxg3+ 32. Qxg3 Qa5 33. Bc1 Bxe2 34. Nxe2 Qxa2 $19) 28... Nfxg4
$17 {retrieving the pawn and seriously weakening the white kingside.}) (25...
Qd8 $1 {[%cal Gf6g4]} 26. Kg1 b5 {leads to similar play.}) 26. Ref2 $6 {
Once again forcing a useful regrouping move.} (26. Nd5 $1 $13 {would still
have been reasonable.}) {[#]} 26... Qd8 $1 $15 {[%cal Gf6g4] Threatening ...
Nfg4.} 27. g5 ({Suba analyzes} 27. Kg1 b5 28. cxb5 Nfxg4 {Indeed, Black has
strong initiative:} 29. hxg4 Nxg4 30. Nce2 Qh4 31. Bf3 Nxf2 32. Rxf2 axb5 $17 {
Black is not worse from a material point of view and has very active play.})
27... hxg5 28. Qxg5 Ne8 $5 ({With the rook on c8 instead of e8, the familiar} 
28... Nh5 {does not work due to} 29. Qxd8+ {with check.}) ({But} 28... Nh7 $1 {
is more active as the knight could later go to g5.}) 29. Qxd8 {Correctly
assesing that the queen exchange somewhat restricts Black's initiative.} ({If} 
29. Qd2 b5 30. cxb5 Nd3 31. Rf3 Bxc3 32. Qxd3 axb5 33. Qxb5 Be5 $17 {[%cal
Ge8g7,Gd8h4,Gc8c2,Gb7c6] Black is much better coordinated and has many
attacking ideas based on ...Ng7, ...Qh4 (possibly after ...Bc6) or ...Rc2.})
29... Rdxd8 {[#]The consequences of the central break clearly favour Black,
who has the better structure and excellent piece activity.} 30. Na4 $6 (30. Nd5
$5 Bxd5 31. exd5 b5 $15) 30... b5 {This always comes as an excellent
complement to ...e6-e5.} 31. Nb6 Rc7 32. cxb5 axb5 33. Rd1 Rc3 34. Nf1 (34. Kh2
Nf6 {planning ...Nfg4+.}) 34... b4 $1 $19 35. Na4 (35. Bxb4 $2 Nd3 $19) 35...
Rd3 36. Rxd3 Nxd3 37. Rd2 Ba6 {The same as in the game with Gheorghiu (see the
previous article), Uhlmann's pieces are dominated by the black knight on d3.}
38. Bb2 Nxb2 39. Nxb2 Rc8 40. Nd3 Bc3 41. Rd1 Nf6 42. Nf4 Be5 43. Nd3 Bxd3 $1
44. Rxd3 Rc1 45. Kg1 Nh5 46. Kf2 Nf4 47. Rd2 Bc3 48. Rxd6 (48. Rxd6 {and
without waiting for} Rc2+ {White resigned. A long time ago, after failing to
achieve anything concrete against Spassky's isolated queen pawn and despite
doing everything as recommended by his countryman Nimzowitsch, Larsen famously
exclaimed: "One needs to grab that pawn, not just block it!" We will now
examine two games played by Gheorghiu with black, trying to cast some light
over this issue, concerning the e4-pawn.}) 0-1

