1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. e4 a6 10. Qe3 O-O 11. Nd4 Qc7 12. b3 Nbd7 13. Bb2 Rfe8 14. Kh1 Bf8 15. f4
g6 16. Rae1 Bg7 17. h3 {[#]} e5 $1 {In the absence of the threat g4-g5, this
is an entirely well-timed break.} 18. Nc2 ({If} 18. fxe5 {any capture is good,
but the simplest is} dxe5 19. Nc2 b5 {achieving counterplay at once.}) 18...
exf4 19. Qxf4 ({White has to conceal the control over e5, as} 19. gxf4 {allows}
Nxe4 {even though 19...b5 is also good.}) 19... Nc5 $1 ({Gheorghiu calls this
a novelty mentioning that} 19... Ne5 {was previously played in
Karpov-Gheorghiu (see below) in a similar position, yielding Black only
equality. Strictly speaking, the game had entered unknown paths earlier, but
the use of the term "novelty" is interesting, as it refers to a new idea. One
way or another, Black's concept is fully justified. White will not have
adequate ways to defend his center.}) 20. Nb4 {[#]} Nh5 $6 {This tempting move
is premature as it releases the pressure on e4.} (20... Nfxe4 {runs into} 21.
Nbd5 $14) ({and} 20... a5 {can be met by} 21. Nb5 Qd7 22. Bxf6 Bxf6 23. Qxf6
axb4 24. Qxd6 $11) ({Black should have resorted to the idea played one move
later at once:} 20... Qd7 $1 {, getting with the queen out of the knights'
range and targeting h3. The point is that the same method as recommended below}
21. Re3 {allows} Nfxe4 $1) 21. Qf2 Qd7 22. Ncd5 $6 {This allows a series of
tactical blows deciding the game in Black's favour.} (22. g4 Nf6 {would still
leave White a bit hanging.}) ({But the complications after} 22. Re3 $1 {
, over defending g3, should peter out in a draw.} Nxe4 23. Rxe4 Rxe4 24. Bxe4
Qxh3+ 25. Kg1 Bxe4 26. Nxe4 Bxb2 27. Qxb2 Re8 28. Nf6+ $1 (28. Qd4 $2 {loses to
} Rxe4 29. Qxe4 Qxf1+ $1 30. Kxf1 Nxg3+) 28... Nxf6 29. Qxf6 {and Black does
not have anything better than a perpetual check with} Qxg3+) 22... Bxd5 $1 23.
Bxg7 (23. Nxd5 Nd3 {wins material.}) 23... Nxe4 $1 24. Rxe4 Bxe4 25. g4 ({Or if
} 25. Bb2 Qxh3+) 25... Nxg7 26. Bxe4 Rxe4 27. Nd5 Re6 $1 28. Qf3 Rb8 {and
without any compensation for the rook White resigned. Let us now examine the
game mentioned by Gheorghiu in his comments:} 0-1

