1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. Rd1 a6 10. e4 Nbd7 11. Qe3 O-O 12. Nd4 Qc7 13. b3 Rfe8 14. Bb2 Bf8 15.
Rac1 Rac8 16. h3 Qb8 17. Re1 g6 18. Rcd1 Nc5 19. f3 Bg7 20. Ba1 $5 {Karpov
immediately anticipates the danger of the pin along the long diagonal before
it becomes real.} Ncd7 21. f4 {[#]} e5 22. Nc2 exf4 23. Qxf4 Ne5 {A solid move
which leads to approximate equality.} ({But Black could have obtained
immediate counterplay with} 23... b5 24. cxb5 (24. Qxd6 Qxd6 25. Rxd6 Bf8 26.
Rdd1 bxc4 {retrieces the pawn with comfortable play.}) 24... Nh5 (24... axb5
25. Rf1 Ne5 26. Nb4 {allows White to consolidate.}) 25. Qd2 ({White can defend
both c3 and g3 with} 25. Qe3 {but this leaves the c2-knight hanging allowing}
axb5 26. Nb4 Be5 {with strong counterplay.}) 25... Nxg3 {with double-edged
play.}) ({The same method as in the previous game is less effective as the
a1-bishop is defended:} 23... Nc5 24. Nb4) 24. Nb4 {The position is rather
static and about equal. But in such situations, Karpov used to be very strong.
The last move targets the c6-square but the chances to invade it are not clear
yet. White will manage to carry it out only with Black's "cooperation".} h5 25.
Rf1 Qc7 26. Kh1 {[#]} Re6 {Since the knight blocks the e-file, the plan
initiated by this move is a bit neutral.} ({Gheorghiu might have come up with
the idea of} 26... Qd7 $5 {as played during the previous game (actually
chronologically later) while analyzing his loss to Karpov. It is worth
mentioning that due to the hanging h3-pawn} 27. a4 {does not prevent} b5 {
for instance:} 28. axb5 axb5 29. Nxb5 ({Or if} 29. cxb5 $6 {Black can use the
same ideas based on the hanging h3 pawn with} Rxc3 $1 30. Bxc3 Nxe4 $1 {and if}
31. Ba1 Nc3 $1) 29... Bxe4 $1 $11 {A familiar trick to retrieve the pawn. The
point is that} 30. Bxe4 $2 Qxh3+ 31. Kg1 Neg4 $19 {threatens mate and attacks
the e4-bishop.}) 27. Qd2 Rce8 28. Ncd5 {White invades this square only after
Black has invested some time in doubling his rooks. Soon Black will need to
waste some time again, but this is more of a psychological success for White.}
Nxd5 29. cxd5 Rf6 $5 ({Interesting and probably viable, but the simpler} 29...
R6e7 30. Rc1 Qd7 {would have maintained the previous character of the position.
}) {[#]} 30. Rf4 $5 {The most principled move aimed at obtaining a mobile
center even at the cost of an exchange.} (30. Rfe1 a5 31. Nd3 Ba6 32. Nxe5 dxe5
{does not offer White too much.}) 30... Rxf4 $2 {Equivalent to a positional
capitulation.} ({Sooner or later Black would have to allow gxf4, but it would
have been better to win an exchange along the way:} 30... Bh6 31. Qf2 Bxf4 32.
gxf4 a5 33. Nc6 ({The same thematic invasion as in the game. If} 33. Nc2 $6
Rxf4 $1 34. Qxf4 Qxc2 {Black maintains his stability while}) (33. Nd3 Nxd3 34.
Rxd3 Qc1+ {wins at least the f4-pawn.}) 33... Bxc6 34. dxc6 Qxc6 35. Qd2 b5 36.
fxe5 dxe5 {The material is about equal and even tough two bishops are usually
worrying, White's king is too exposed to claim an advantage.}) 31. gxf4 Nd7 32.
Bxg7 Kxg7 {[#]} 33. Nc6 $1 {White's domination is complete now and Karpov will
win quickly.} Kg8 (33... Bxc6 34. Qc3+ Kg8 35. dxc6 $16) 34. e5 Kh7 (34... dxe5
35. d6 Qc8 36. Ne7+) 35. Rc1 dxe5 $2 {A blunder which loses at once.} (35...
Rc8 {would have prolonged the agony but hardly changed the result. White would
have had to find the best way of playing e5-e6 and conclude his attack on the
kingside.}) 36. Nxe5 Qd6 37. Nxf7 Qf6 38. Ng5+ Kg8 39. Rc7 Nc5 40. b4 Qd6 41.
Rf7 1-0

