{[#] It may seem that after Black's earlier ...e6-e5 and ...b6-b5 White has
stabilized the position and enjoys a comfortable plus. Do you find a way to
keep Black's counterplay alive?!} 23... h5 $1 {This strong positional move
threatens to shake White's stability on the dark squares with ...h5-h4.} 24.
Rf2 $6 ({It would have been safer to release the tension with} 24. f5 {, but
Black's last move would have been useful anyway as it slows down the advance
of the g-pawn. Black could continue with} Rc8 {[%cal Gb8a7,Gd7b6,Gb6c4]
followed by ...Qa7+, ...Nb6-c4 with "insanely pleasant play", as the Russians
say.}) 24... h4 $1 25. fxe5 $6 {After playing this dubious move White offered
a draw which was prematurely accepted by Black.} ({The best way to maintain
approximate equality was} 25. g4 exf4 26. g5 Nh5 27. g6 $1 ({It is best to
weaken Black's kingside as after} 27. Bf1 g6 28. Qxb5 Qd8 29. Nf3 Bg7 30. Qa5
Qc8 {Black retains dangerous threats against the white king, while he is in
absolute safety.}) 27... fxg6 28. Bf1 Ne5 29. Qxb5 Qd8 30. Nf3 $13 {with White
counterplay.}) (25. gxh4 $6 {is no better than the game move:} exf4 26. Rxf4
Ne5 27. Qb3 (27. Qe2 d5 28. Rf2 Qb6 29. h5 d4 $36 {with perfect control on the
dark squares.}) 27... Qa7+ 28. Kh2 (28. Kh1 Nh5) 28... d5 $36) (25. fxe5 {
After the game move, Black could have continued with} Nxe5 $1 26. Bxe5 (26. Qe3
hxg3 27. Qxg3 {allows the dangerous attack starting with} Re6 28. Nb3 Nfd7 29.
Nd4 Rg6 $17 {Marin}) 26... dxe5 27. g4 (27. gxh4 Nh5 $1 $17 {invades f4 soon.})
27... Rd8 $1 $17 {with serious structural problems for White and dangerous
black initiative (Gheorghiu)}) 1/2-1/2

