{[#]White's queen is obviously exposed in the center. Is there a way to take
advantage of this circumstance?} 23... Nc5 $1 {The knight is taboo, Black
threatens with the fork ...Nb3 and also to win the e4-pawn with ...e6-e5, the
thematic move in this article.} (23... e5 {only leaves Black with problems
along the d-file.} 24. Qd3 $16) ({If} 23... g6 {Black is not in time to
threaten the queen with ...¥g7 because of the weakness on d6.} 24. Red1 $1)
24. Rc2 (24. bxc5 dxc5 $19) 24... e5 {Black simply loses a pawn.} 25. Qd1 Ncxe4
26. Nxe4 Bxe4 (26... Nxe4 27. Nd5 Nf6 (27... Bxd5 28. Qxd5 Nf6 29. Qb7 $44 {
Kasparov}) 28. Nxf6+ gxf6 29. Qg4+ Bg7 30. Bc1 Bxg2+ 31. Kxg2 Qb7+ 32. Kg1 Qd7
$15) 27. Bxe4 Nxe4 28. Qf3 (28. Nd5 Rxc4 $1 29. Qd3 Rdc8 $1 30. Qxc4 Rxc4 31.
Rxc4 Nxf2+ 32. Kg2 Nd3 33. Re2 Qb7 $19 {Kasparov}) 28... Nf6 29. Rd1 Qa7 $1 (
29... b5 $6 30. c5 dxc5 31. Rxd8 Rxd8 32. bxc5 $13 {Kasparov}) 30. g4 {[><d5]}
