{The Hedgehog is a very transpositional opening where knowing the general
plans is as important as the concrete theory. In the early phase, it is useful
to know the best move orders. Then, however, everything gradually becomes a
matter of individual choice. This is why in many lines I have given
alternatives for Black to the main lines as my aim is to give a complete
picture of the possible plans. One final warning: Engines are very optimistic
for white in the beginning probably due to his space advantage. But they tend
to come back to reality in the early middlegame. So don't be discouraged if at
any time you read "+0.50"!} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7
6. O-O a6 {This move order is primarily aimed to neutralize White's positional
ideas in the lines with b2-b3 (these lines are covered in Part 2). The main
idea is to delay the weakening of the c6-square until White plays d4 followed
by Qxd4. If instead Nxd4 the pawn will stay on d7 for a bit longer.} (6... Be7
{exposes Black to the variation} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. Bg5 a6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6
11. Qf4 {True, things are not entirely clear here and it is a pure matter of
taste whether to allow this or not. Personally, I prefer to avoid it.}) 7. d4
cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. Bg5 {This line has independent value only if White plays
Rad1 as in the main line. Otherwise, it would transpose to one of the lines
below (5 to 8)} (9. Ng5 {speeds up the knight transfer to e4 by omitting Rd1
in order to deprive Black of the fighting resource ...Ne8 (compare with lines
2 to 4).} Bxg2 10. Kxg2 Nc6 11. Qf4 Be7 12. Nce4 ({More active than} 12. Nge4
Nxe4 13. Qxe4 Rc8 14. b3 Bf6 15. Bd2 O-O 16. Rac1 Qc7 17. Rfd1 Qb8 18. a4 Rfd8
19. Bf4 Na5 20. Qb1 Qa8+ 21. e4 d5 22. exd5 Bxc3 23. Rxc3 exd5 $36 {Akesson,R 
(2466)-Hillarp Persson,T (2491) Vaxjo 2008 (0-1, 93)}) (12. Rd1 {transposes to
one of the lines below (2-4).}) 12... O-O ({Since there is no early pressure
on d6, Black can also regroup with} 12... Qc7 13. Rd1 Rd8 $11) 13. Nxf6+ Bxf6
14. Nxh7 $5 {White wins a pawn but will face problems to complete the
development due to the active f6-bishop.} (14. Rd1 h6 15. Nf3 Ne5 $11) 14...
Kxh7 15. Qe4+ Kg8 16. Qxc6 Rc8 17. Qe4 (17. Qa4 d5 18. cxd5 Qxd5+ {also offers
Black ample compensation.}) (17. Qb7 Rxc4 18. Qxa6 Qc7 $44 {Black is well
coordinated and b2 and e2 need permanent care. On top, there is the threat ...
Qc6+ followed by ...Ra8.}) 17... Qc7 18. Rd1 Rfd8 ({It does not make sense to
give away the d6-pawn with} 18... Qxc4 $6 19. Qxc4 Rxc4 20. Rxd6 $14 {Adorjan,
A (2545)-Suba,M (2520) Budapest 1993 (½-½, 27)}) 19. Be3 Qxc4 20. Qxc4 Rxc4
21. Bxb6 Rd7 $11 {for instance} 22. Rab1 Rc2) (9. Be3 {bears some similarity
with Line 9 below.} Nbd7 10. Ng5 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Rc8 {Since White has hurried to
define his plans, Black can switch to another defensive system.} (11... Be7 12.
Nge4 Qc7 13. Rfd1 O-O 14. Nxd6 {transposes to a setup we avoid in Line 9, even
though it remains playable.}) 12. Nge4 Rc6 {The similar position with Bg5
instead of Be3 is supposed to favor White. But the bishop is more passive on
e3 as it fails to put real pressure on Black.} 13. Nxf6+ (13. Rfd1 {Schmidt,P 
(2407)-Janz,F (2372) Austria 2004 (½-½, 17)} Be7 14. Rac1 O-O 15. f3 Qc8 16.
b3 Rd8 $11) 13... Nxf6 14. Rac1 (14. Ne4 Be7 15. b4 d5 16. cxd5 Qxd5 {The
knight is pinned!} 17. Qxd5 Nxd5 $15 {Pogorelov,R (2415) -Ionescu,C (2440)
Berga 1994 (0-1, 51)}) 14... Be7 15. Ne4 O-O $10 16. Rfd1 Qc7 (16... d5 $11)
17. b3 {Piket,J (2495)-Prie,E (2435) Cannes 1990 (½-½, 56)} d5 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6
19. Qg4 dxc4 20. Rxc4 Rxc4 21. Qxc4 Qb7+ 22. f3 Rc8 $11 {These resources based
on ...d6-d5 are not available in the lines with Bg5 instead of Be3.}) 9... Nbd7
10. Nd2 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Be7 12. Nde4 Qc7 13. Rad1 (13. Rfd1 {transposes to
either one of the Lines 5 to 8.}) 13... O-O 14. Nxd6 {The critical move as
otherwise Black is under no pressure since White's rooks are not optimally
placed for the normal slow fight.} (14. b3 h6 15. Bc1 Rfd8 16. f3 b5 17. Ba3 (
17. cxb5 d5 18. Nf2 Rdc8 19. Bb2 e5 20. Qd3 d4 21. Nce4 Nd5 $17) 17... Nc5 18.
Nf2 d5 19. cxd5 {Gamundi Salamanca,A (2464)-Suba,M (2487) Barcelona 2000 (0-1,
72)} exd5 $15 {The queen is a bad blockading piece, the knights are far from
d4, so the isolated queen pawn is a strong one!}) (14. Nxf6+ Nxf6 15. Ne4 Nxe4
16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Qxe4 b5 18. f3 bxc4 19. Qxc4 d5 20. Qd4 Rfc8 21. Rc1 Qb7 $11
{Davidovic,A (2405)-Makropoulos,G (2460) Dortmund 1988 (½-½, 26)}) 14... Rfd8
{White is hanging now and needs to be careful to avoid losing a piece.} (14...
Rad8 {is also frequently played, but I find the main line move better as the
rooks belong on the c- and d-file. Besides, in some lines the queen's rook can
become active along the a-file.}) 15. Nce4 (15. b4 {prepares to sustain the
knight with c4-c5 if needed but weakens c4.} h6 16. Bxf6 (16. Be3 {offers
Black the useful extra tempo '''h7-h6 with respect to the lines with Be3.} Bxd6
$5 17. Qxd6 Qxc4 {and the white rooks are obviously misplaced.}) 16... Nxf6 17.
c5 a5 18. a3 axb4 19. axb4 bxc5 20. bxc5 Ra5 $11) (15. Nde4 Ne5 16. Qe3 Nxc4
17. Qc1 Qb7 $11) 15... h6 16. Bf4 (16. Bh4 $2 {Pogorelov,R (2445)-Marin,M 
(2520) Badalona 1995 (½-½, 21)} g5 17. Nxg5 hxg5 18. Bxg5 Bxd6 19. Qxd6 Qxc4
$17) 16... Nc5 17. Qe3 Qc6 18. f3 Ncxe4 19. Nxe4 Qxc4 $11 *

