1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. Rd1 {Before undertaking anything concrete, White increases the pressure
on d6 with a neutral move.} Be7 10. Ng5 {One of the ways White can put big
pressure on d6. In the first phase it will look as if he will have the
initiative but in the long run, he risks being pushed back by the black pawns.}
Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Nc6 {After the earlier exchange the knight stands well on this
square as it does not obstruct the bishop. It now forces the queen to leave
the most active square on board and prevents a later intrusion on c6.} 12. Qf4
(12. Qd2 {is more passive.} O-O 13. b3 Qc7 14. Bb2 (14. Nge4 Ne8 {more about
this apparently passive retreat soon in the main line.} 15. f3 Rd8 16. a4 h6
17. Ba3 f5 {Now and later we will see that this way of gaining space offers
Black good counterplay.} 18. Nf2 Bg5 19. f4 Bf6 20. Qe3 Rf7 21. Rac1 Re7 $11 {
Mikhalchishin,A (2525)-Tukmakov,V (2575) Kuibyshev 1986 (½-½, 31)}) 14... Qb7
15. f3 Rfd8 16. Qf4 {Winants,L (2500)-Anagnostopoulos,D (2425) Val Thorens
1994 (½-½, 42)} h6 17. Nge4 Ne8 18. h4 {Taking measures against the kingside
expansion but leaving the queenside unattended.} b5 $15) 12... O-O 13. Nge4 {
Somewhat rigid.} ({The slightly more flexible} 13. Nce4 {[%emt 0:00:02] is
examined in Line}) ({and} 13. b3 {is examined in Line 3.}) 13... Ne8 {This is
a typical way of keeping the game tense. By keeping the knights on board,
Black intends to play ...f7-f5 in the near future, gaining space and causing
White some coordination problems.} ({But the simplyfying} 13... Nxe4 {is also
good for equality:} 14. Nxe4 (14. Qxe4 {Sanguinetti,R (2480)-Rogoff,K (2480)
Biel 1976 (1-0, 85)} Qd7 $5 $146 {This is the best square for the queen as it
sustains ...f7-f5 and in some cases ...b6-b5. The chances are about equal. For
instance:} 15. f3 f5 16. Qe3 b5 $5 17. cxb5 Nb4 18. Qd2 axb5 $132) 14... Ra7
15. b3 Rd7 16. Ba3 (16. Bb2 $2 {Csom,I (2505)-Kindermann,S (2485) Biel 1986 
(1-0, 36)} f5 $1 17. Nd2 e5 18. Qe3 d5 $17) (16. Nc3 $5 d5 17. cxd5 exd5 $15 {
Since White cannot prevent ... d5-d4 the isolated queen pawn is very strong.})
(16. Ng5 $146 {looks like a safer way of retaining approximate equality.})
16... f5 $1 17. Nxd6 e5 18. Qf3 (18. Qd2 Nd4 19. c5 $8 bxc5 20. Nc4 Qa8+ 21. f3
Rfd8 $15) 18... e4 19. Qf4 Bg5 20. Nb7 $8 Qf6 21. Qxg5 Qxg5 22. Rxd7 Re8 {
with just some compensation for the queen as Black can start an attack with ...
f5-f4 while defending his seventh rank with ...Re7.}) 14. b3 Ra7 {Another
typical way to regroup for this line. With bishops on board, this would have
been more complicated to achieve. The rook is heading for d7 in order to
over-defend d6.} (14... f5 15. Ng5 Qd7 16. Qe3 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Rb8 18. a4 e5 {
with kingside attacking chances is also worth a try. The weakness on d5 is
less relevant after Black has exchanged his potentially bad bishop.}) 15. Ba3
$5 {This was recommended after the game by my opponent in the game below.} (15.
f3 f5 (15... h6 16. Qe3 Rd7 17. Ba3 Qb8 18. Rac1 $14 {Csom-Stocek, Budapest
1998}) 16. Nf2 Bf6 17. Qe3 Re7 {b5} 18. Rb1 Rff7 $11) (15. Bb2 $2 f5 $1 $36 16.
Nd2 Bg5 17. Qf3 Ne5 18. Qh5 Bf6 19. Qh3 g5 (19... Ng4 20. Kg1 b5 $36) 20. Kg1
g4 21. Qg2 h5 $17 {Hoeksema,E-Marin,M (2551) Groningen 2008 (0-1, 36) A
perfect kingside expansion version.}) 15... Rd7 16. Qe3 $5 {Trying to keep e6
under observation as suggested by Hoeksema} (16. Rac1 $2 f5 17. Nd2 Bg5 18. Qf3
Ne5 19. Qh5 Bh6 20. Rc2 Nf6 $36) (16. h4 h6 17. Qe3 d5 {This works out well
after the insertion of king pawns' moves as White does not have Ng5.} 18. Bxe7
Nxe7 19. cxd5 exd5 20. Qd3 d4 $17) 16... f5 $1 {It appears that the weakness
on e6 is not so relevant due to Black's activity.} (16... Nf6 {/\Ng4, f5} 17.
Nxf6+ $1 Bxf6 18. Rac1 $14) (16... d5 17. cxd5 exd5 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 19. Qd3 d4
20. Ng5 $5) 17. Nd2 Rf7 18. Nf3 (18. Qxe6 Nd4 19. Qd5 Nc2 20. Bb2 Nxa1 21. Bxa1
Nc7 22. Qd3 Bf6 $13) 18... Bf6 19. Bb2 Ne5 $11 {Black is well regrouped and
has no problems at all.} *

