1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. Rd1 Be7 10. Ng5 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Nc6 12. Qf4 O-O 13. Nce4 {This is more
flexible than 13.Nge4 as it keeps the possibility of the harmonious regrouping
with Nf3.} Ne8 $1 (13... Nxe4 $2 14. Qxe4 {wins at least a pawn.}) 14. b3 Ra7
15. Bb2 Rd7 ({A consistent move but the immediate} 15... b5 $5 {is also
possible.} 16. Nf3 (16. cxb5 $6 axb5 {/\ d5, Qa8|^}) 16... bxc4 (16... Qa8 17.
Rac1 h6 {Wojtkiewicz,A (2580)-Ftacnik,L (2535) Budapest 1993 (0-1, 58)} 18. c5
d5 19. Nd6 $14 Bxd6 20. cxd6 {[%cal Ge2e4]} Rd7 21. e4 Rxd6 22. e5 Rd7 23. Ba3
Ne7 24. Nd4 $36) 17. bxc4 Rc7 $11) 16. Rac1 {Completing the development and
taking measures against ...b6-b5.} (16. Nf3 {does not really inhibit} f5 $5 ({
On top,} 16... b5 {seems to equalize:} 17. Kg1 bxc4 18. bxc4 Na5 19. Rac1 Rc7
$11 {Adorjan,A (2565)-Rohde,M (2400) New York 1985 (1-0, 42)}) 17. Nc3 (17.
Neg5 e5 18. Qe3 Bxg5 19. Nxg5 f4 20. gxf4 Rxf4 21. Ne6 Rg4+ 22. Kh1 Qe7 23. Qf3
Qxe6 24. Qxc6 Rh4 $132 {<Bb2}) 17... Bf6 18. Qe3 Re7 19. Rd2 Qc7 20. Rad1 Ne5 {
/\Rf7, Ng4} 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. f4 Bf6 23. Qf3 g5 $132) 16... Nc7 {An
interesting, non-typical move. Black defends e6 in advance in order to prepare
...f7-f5 and, at the same time, this move also sustains ...b6-b5 or ...d6-d5.}
(16... Qa8 17. Kg1 (17. Nf3 Qb7 18. Kg1 h6 {/\b5} 19. Rd2 $4 f5 20. Nc3 e5 21.
Qe3 e4 22. Nxe4 fxe4 23. Qxe4 Nd8 $17 {Tukmakov-Ribli, Las Palmas 1982}) 17...
b5 (17... h6 18. Nf3 Qb7 $11 {/\b5}) 18. Nf3 (18. Qg4 $5 {/\Nxe6} Nd8) 18...
bxc4 $6 {Prematurely opening the queenside and thereby allowing White to
activate his forces.} (18... Qb7 $5 $11) 19. Rxc4 d5 20. Nc5 Rd8 21. Rcc1 $16 {
Van der Sterren,P (2470)-Kindermann,S (2500) Munich 1988 (½-½, 104)}) 17. Nf3
(17. h4 {does not relly prevent} f5 18. Nc3 e5 19. Qd2 Bxg5 20. hxg5 f4 21. Ne4
$13) 17... f5 18. Nc3 g5 $1 {Taking over the initative.} 19. Qd2 (19. Qe3 g4
20. Nd2 ({Not} 20. Nd4 Bg5 21. Nxc6 Bxe3 22. Nxd8 Bxc1 {winning an exchange.})
20... Bg5 21. Qxb6 {"was another, computer-like option. I thought that I would
have very good counterplay after"} Qa8 22. f3 $8 {and now just 22...Ne5 or
even 22...Rb8 23.Qf2 Ne5 gives Black active piece play and good compensation
for a pawn." (Carlsen).}) 19... g4 20. Ne1 (20. Nd4 $6 {would be worse, since
now} Bg5 21. e3 Ne5 {leaves the knight practically untouchable on e5. Note
that it also makes it more difficult to create active play for White since b4
and c5 would be almost impossible to carry out as Rxd4 and a knight move to f3
would probably be strong then. (Carlsen).}) 20... Bg5 {Forcing the chronical
weakening of the f3-square.} 21. e3 Rff7 22. Kg1 Ne8 23. Ne2 Nf6 (23... e5 $5 {
/\...Nf6}) 24. Nf4 (24. Bxf6 {was safer.}) 24... Ne4 (24... Qe8 {Kramnik,V 
(2799)-Carlsen,M (2733) Wijk aan Zee 2008 (0-1, 57)} 25. Bxf6 $1) 25. Qe2 (25.
Nxe6 $2 {This was what Carlsen feared, but after the game, he analyzed the
following lines:} Qe8 26. Nxg5 Nxd2 27. Nxf7 {I don't really understand why
though, since, as any engine points out,} Ne4 28. Nh6+ Kf8 {with the point
that 29.Nxf5 Qf7 wins for Black.}) 25... Qe8 $36 {with good play on the light
squares.} *

