1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. Rd1 Be7 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Nd2 {After completing the neutral developing
moves with a direct or indirect pressure on d6, White finally transfers the
knight to e4.} Bxg2 12. Kxg2 O-O 13. Nde4 Qc7 14. Rac1 ({Even though Rfd1 is
basically more natural than Rad1 as in Line 1, for the purpose of capturing
the pawn things are slightly worse here:} 14. Nxd6 $6 Rfd8 15. b4 (15. Nde4 Ne5
16. Qe3 Nxc4 17. Qf3 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Bxg5 19. Nxg5 h6 20. Ne4 Nxb2 $15 {
Schneider,A (2302)-Berczes,D (2261) Budapest 2003 (0-1, 82)}) {Drazic,S (2546)
-Teplyi,I (2408) Skanderborg 2010 (1-0, 22)} 15... h6 16. Bxf6 (16. Be3 a5 {
makes clear that in this concrete position the rook is hanging on a1.}) 16...
Bxf6 17. Qe3 Be5 18. Nde4 Qxc4 {with at least equal play. Among others, the
c3-knight is pinned.}) (14. Nxf6+ Nxf6 15. Ne4 Nxe4 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Qxe4 {
This is an irritating line, I admit. White openly plays for a draw.} Rac8 (
17... b5 $6 {is less indicated than in a similar position from Line 1 as a2 is
defended after} 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Qb4 $14) 18. Rd4 (18. a4 Qc7 19. b3 {
Krivonosov,O (2457)-Carow,J (2264) Hofheim 2013 (1-0, 87)} Qc6 $11) 18... b5
19. Rad1 Rxc4 20. Rxc4 bxc4 21. Qxc4 Qb7+ 22. e4 (22. Kg1 {Frois,A (2370)
-Rocha,S (2412) Merida 2008 (½-½, 26)} d5 $11) 22... Rd8 $11 {followed by ...
d6-d5}) 14... Rfd8 15. f3 ({As in a line above White has the irritating} 15.
Nxf6+ Nxf6 (15... Bxf6 {also leads to plain equality:} 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. f3
Rac8 18. Ne4 Ne8 19. Rc3 h6 20. Rb3 d5 21. cxd5 Rxd5 $11 {Frois,A (2350)-Suba,
M (2535) Zaragoza 1997 (½-½, 52)}) 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Qxe4 Rac8
19. Rc3 h6 20. Rcd3 b5 21. b3 Rc5 22. Rd4 bxc4 23. bxc4 Qc7 $11 {The
weaknesses on c4 and d6 compensate for echother, Krivonosov,O (2200)-Ionescu,C
(2480) Vosu 1989 (½-½, 34)}) 15... h6 16. Nxf6+ (16. Be3 {is inconsequent.}
Ne8 17. Bf4 {Oms Pallisse,J (2506)-Aroshidze,L (2560) Barcelona 2012 (½-½,
34)} Qb7 $11 {Black threatens to equalize with ...b6-b5 but also puts pressure
on the long diagonal.} 18. a4 $6 Nc5 19. Rc2 g5 20. Bc1 f5 21. Nf2 Bf6 22. Qd2
Ng7 $36 {White's coordination is very poor.}) 16... Nxf6 17. Be3 {This
position was reached in several games including Smyslov,V (2600)-Portisch,L 
(2635) Ljubljana 1985 (½-½, 19). The most accurate move seems to be} Qd7 $5
$146 {threatening ...b6-b5 and removing the queen from the exposed file.} 18.
a4 (18. Qxb6 Rdb8 19. Qa5 Rxb2 $11) 18... d5 19. cxd5 (19. Qf4 Rab8 {Defending
b6.} 20. cxd5 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 exd5 22. Rd3 Re8 $11 {The backward e2-pawn is as
weak as the isolated queen pawn. In some lines a4 is also hanging.}) 19... Bc5
20. Qe5 Nxd5 21. Bxc5 bxc5 22. b3 Qc6 $11 {Once again the mutual weaknsses
compensate for each other.} *

