1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. Rd1 Be7 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Qd2 {This is one of the most consistent systems
based on Bg5. White avoids early simplifications and prepares Bf4 more or less
forcing the knight retreat ...Ne8. But as we know, this involves a lot of
potential dynamism for Black.} O-O (11... Rc8 {leads to an almost symmetrical
position with active white play in the spirit of the Catalan Opening,
something Black wishes to avoid when playing the Hedgehog.} 12. Bf4 Rxc4 (12...
e5 $6 13. Bg5 Rxc4 $2 14. Nxe5 $1) 13. Bxd6 Bxd6 14. Qxd6 $14 {Black's results
in this line are very poor.}) 12. Bf4 Ne8 13. Ng5 {A familiar operation
carried out in a slightly different form.} ({For} 13. Rac1 {see Line 8.}) 13...
Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Rc8 15. b3 (15. Nge4 Rc6 16. Rac1 h6 $15 {followed by ...g7-g5
and ...f7-f5 soon, when White's pieces stand in each others' way.}) 15... h6 {
The simplest move forcing White to display his cards.} ({To over the board
players} 15... b5 {looks premature as it leads to forcing play with incomplete
development. But such abstract inhibitions do not work in correspondence games.
} 16. cxb5 (16. Nge4 bxc4 17. Bxd6 Nxd6 18. Nxd6 Bxd6 19. Qxd6 cxb3 20. Na4 b2
21. Nxb2 Rc2 $11 22. Rab1 Qa8+ 23. Kg1 Nf6 $15) 16... axb5 17. Nxb5 Rc5 18.
Nxd6 Qa8+ {Preparing ...Rd5.} (18... Rd5 $6 {allows} 19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. Qe3 {
with three pawns for the piece and better structure.}) (18... Nxd6 {also looks
insufficient for complete equality:} 19. Bxd6 Bxg5 20. Qe1 Qa8+ 21. Kg1 Rfc8
22. Bxc5 Nxc5 23. h4 Bf6 24. Rac1 $14 {Krivonosov,O (2440)-Kristjansson,S 
(2389) ICC INT 2002 (1-0, 43)}) 19. Nde4 Bxg5 20. Bxg5 Qxe4+ (20... Rd5 21. Qe3
f5 22. f3 fxe4 23. Qxe4 Nc7 24. Rxd5 exd5 25. Qe7 Qe8 {also offers White
reasonable compensation.}) 21. f3 Qc6 22. Qxd7 Qxd7 23. Rxd7 Rxg5 {Black is a
piece up but the queenside pawns are threatening. It is obvious, though, that
White cannot hope for more than a draw, for instance:} 24. a4 Nf6 25. Rb7 Ra8
26. a5 Rd5 27. a6 Rd7 28. b4 Kf8 29. Rxd7 Nxd7 30. b5 Ke7 31. Rc1 Kd8 32. Rc6
Nb8 33. Rc2 Nd7 $11 {This line requires some further investigation, of course,
as the play is very rich in possibilities and dynamic.}) 16. Nge4 $5 ({As
usual in such situations} 16. Nf3 {is a flexible alternative.} Rc6 {This looks
safest.} (16... Qc7 17. Ne4 {forces Black to weaken the d5-square with} e5 {
but since the white knight is on e4 Black gets some time to organize his
counterplay.} 18. Be3 (18. Bxh6 $6 {is unsound:} Qb7 $1 19. Nc3 gxh6 20. Qxh6
Ndf6 21. Kg1 Ne4 $1 22. Nd5 b5 $5 $17) 18... Qb7 19. Nc3 Nef6 20. Kg1 {Hansen,
L-Stangl, M, Germany 2002 (½-½, 52)} b5 21. Nh4 (21. cxb5 {reduces White's
control on d5, which is important as he cannot play e2-e4 easily. The e3
bishop is some sort of spectator standing in the way of its own pieces and
pawns.} axb5 22. Nh4 Rfe8 23. Nf5 Bf8 24. Nd5 Re6 {with a solid position.})
21... bxc4 22. Nf5 Rfe8 23. Rab1 Bf8 $11 {The weakness of the c4-pawn
compensates for the d5-square.}) 17. g4 {One of the very few active tries.} (
17. Rac1 Qa8 18. e4 Bf6 19. Be3 Bxc3 20. Qxc3 Nef6 21. Qd4 Rfc8 {followed by ..
.b6-b5 and eventually ...e6-e5. The knights are not weaker than the bishop and
White's light squares (including e4) are vulnerable.}) 17... Nef6 18. g5 hxg5
19. Nxg5 (19. Bxg5 Rc5 {[%cal Gb6b5,Gd8a8] followed by ...b6-b5 and possibly ..
. Qa8.}) 19... Nh5 20. Be3 b5 21. cxb5 Rxc3 22. Qxc3 Bxg5 23. Rxd6 {Georgiev,
K-Adams,M/Tilburg 1992 (0-1, 50)} Be7 24. Rd3 Nhf6 $15) 16... Rc6 ({Once again
starting to advance the pawns makes sense.} 16... e5 17. Be3 f5 18. Qd5+ Kh8
19. Nd2 b5 $132) 17. f3 Qc7 18. Rac1 Qb7 19. a4 (19. g4 {is too slow with the
unstable queenside.} b5 20. cxb5 axb5 21. a4 bxa4 22. bxa4 Ndf6 $15 {Black's
chances are better due to his compact center Cvetkovic, S (2374)-Iordachescu,
V (2579) Subotica 2008 (½-½, 42)}) 19... Nc5 {I am not sure whether at the
height of this game this was necessary. But I had already "prepared" my later
blunder.} ({Now I would prefer} 19... f5 20. Nf2 g5 21. Be3 Bf6 {keeping ...
Nc5 in reserve.}) 20. Rb1 f5 (20... Nf6 $2 21. Nxd6 $1 {Georgiev,K (2645)
-Marin, M (2583) Benasque 2009 (½-½, 97) simply lost a pawn. I overlooked
that after} Bxd6 22. Bxd6 Rd8 {White has} 23. Qf4 $18) 21. Nf2 (21. Nxc5 bxc5 {
opens the b-file against the weakness on b3.}) 21... Bf6 $11 {Black has gained
space and defends all his relative weaknesses.} *

