1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. Rd1 Be7 10. Bg5 Nbd7 11. Qd2 O-O 12. Bf4 Ne8 13. Rac1 {By delaying Ng5,
White invites his opponent to make a useful move while waiting for the
opportunity of ...Bxg2 followed by ...Rc6.} Rc8 14. b3 h6 $5 {My favorite
among a wide range of moves. Black has a compact way to regroup and simply
prevents the knight jump to g5. As usual, White must count with the
possibility of ..g7-g5.} 15. Ne1 {White chooses another path for his knight.
Alternatively he can start a slow kingside attack or occupy the centre.} (15.
h4 $5 Ndf6 16. Ne1 (16. Bxh6 gxh6 17. Qxh6 Ng4 18. Qh5 Nef6 19. Qg5+ Kh8 $19)
16... Qc7 17. Qd3 Bxg2 18. Nxg2 {Archangelsky,M (2210)-Marin,M (2548) Erts
Andorra 2011 (0-1, 52)} Qb7 $5 $11 {Black controls the long diagonal and plans
...Ng4-e5 followed by ...Nf6. If f2-f3 then ...Nh5.}) (15. g4 Nc5 $5 $146 ({
Safer than} 15... Qc7 16. h4 {Piasetski,L (2289)-Marin,M (2548) Benasque 2011 
(½-½, 41). In order to avoid the problems I had in the game I should have
gone for something radical like} Ne5 17. g5 Ng6 {with sharp play.}) 16. h4 (16.
Bg3 Ne4 17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Ne1 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 b5 $11) 16... e5 $5 17. Be3 Bxf3
18. Bxf3 Bxh4 {Black's light squares are terribly weak but after ...Ne6 and ...
Bg5 he will also have his play on the dark squares. If we also count the extra
pawn, Black is doing OK.}) ({Twenty-two years earlier, my main game opponent
treated this same position in a more aggressive way:} 15. e4 Qc7 16. h4 Qb8 17.
g4 {Georgiev,K (2590)-Sokolov,A (2645)/Leningrad 1987/CBM 003 (1/2, 31). I
planned to open the queenside with:} b5 18. cxb5 axb5 19. Nxb5 Rxc1 20. Rxc1
Bxe4 21. a4 Qb7 22. Ne1 Bxg2 23. Nxg2 Nc5 $13) 15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2 (16. Nxg2 {
is likely to cause a waste of time as the knight would be mainly heading to d3
anyway.} Rc6 17. f3 (17. Qd3 Nef6 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Qxe4 Qc8 20. Ne1 Nf6 21. Qf3
d5 $11 {L'Ami,E (2611)-Marin,M (2548) Brasov (rapid) 2011 (½-½, 25).}) 17...
Qc8 18. Be3 Qb7 19. a4 Nef6 20. Bf2 Rfc8 21. e4 Nc5 {Both sides are well
regrouped but making further progress is not simple for either player. The
following phase is typical for hedgehog manoeuvring.} 22. Qb2 Ne8 23. Nf4 Bf6
24. Qa2 g6 25. Nce2 R6c7 26. b4 Nd7 27. Nd3 Be7 28. Be3 h5 29. Rc2 Bf8 30. Rdc1
Nef6 {Threatening ...Nxe4. Judging from the course of the game my opponent did
not notice that, but I was lucky on the first occasion.} 31. Qb3 Ne8 32. Kg2
Nef6 33. Bf4 Nh7 {Threatening ...g5. White already needs to weaken his
position a bit.} 34. h4 Nhf6 35. Qa2 $2 Nxe4 $1 $19 {Iturrizaga,E (2603)-Marin,
M (2548), Vallés (rapid) 2011 (0-1, 59). The game was decisive for my team 
(Foment Barcelona) promotion to the Division de Honor.}) 16... Qc7 17. f3 Qb7
18. Ne4 Nc5 19. Nf2 ({After the blunder in Benasque against the same opponent 
(see Line 7), I triple checked the capture} 19. Nxd6 $2 Nxd6 20. Bxd6 Rfd8 21.
Qf4 Bg5 $19) 19... b5 ({Once again it is dangerous to leave the pawn
undefended.} 19... Nf6 20. Bxd6 (20. e4 Rfd8 21. Ned3 b5 $11) 20... Rcd8 21.
Qf4 g5 22. Bxe7 $1 (22. Qe5 $2 Rxd6 23. Rxd6 Qc7 24. Rcd1 Ne8 $17) 22... gxf4
