Nf4 d5 20. cxd5 Rxc3 21. dxe6 fxe6 22. Nxe6 {Matuszewski,M (2485)-Ponizil,C 
(2478) Poland 2017 (½-½, 95)} Qd6 $1 {Black keeps his material advantage.}) (
{Or} 14. f3 Rc6 15. Nce4 Qb8 16. Nxf6+ Nxf6 17. Qd3 h6 18. Ne4 Rfc8 19. Bf4
Nxe4 20. Qxe4 b5 $11 {Cramling,D (2345)-Ornstein,A (2475) Gavle 1982 (½-½,
23)}) (14. Nge4 {is as always an alternative to the main line.} Ne8 15. h4 h6
16. b3 f5 17. Nd2 Bf6 18. Qd3 Ne5 19. Qb1 Qe7 20. Bd4 b5 $132 21. cxb5 axb5 $11
{Moehring,G (2350)-Boensch,U (2365)/Groeditz 1976/EXT 2001 (1/2, 38)}) 14...
Rc6 (14... Ne8 {is less adequate now, because after} 15. Qd3 Ne5 16. Qb1 $14 {
the threat against h7 forces Black to make a concession.}) 15. Nxf6+ Nxf6 (
15... Bxf6 $2 16. Qe4 $18) 16. Qd3 Qa8 17. Kg1 Rfc8 (17... h6 18. Nf3 Rfc8 $11
{would have been simpler. Black has no problems at all.}) 18. Bd4 {Beliavsky,A
(2619)-Gritsak,O (2539) Aix les Bains 2011 (1-0, 49)} e5 ({Or else} 18... g6
19. Qf3 e5 {with the same idea.} 20. Be3 b5 $132) 19. Be3 b5 20. cxb5 Rxc1 21.
Rxc1 Rxc1+ 22. Bxc1 axb5 23. Qxb5 h6 24. Nf3 Qxa2 $11) 13... Ne8 (13... Qc7 14.
Nxd6 Rad8 {leads to a position which is very similar to some we have seen
before. But in this concrete position, White has some chances to retain an
edge. His rooks are well placed and his bishop is not only safer than on g5
but also controls c5 for b2-b4 and c4-c5.} 15. b4 {This is the only way to
avoid trouble.} (15. Nde4 Ng4 16. Nd2 (16. Bf4 {Gorovets,A (2518)-Akshayraj,K 
(2472) New York 2015 (0-1, 100)} Nde5 17. Bxe5 Nxe5 $17) 16... f5 17. Nb3 g5
18. Qd2 {½-½ Freisler,P (2415)-Laux,T (2320) Prague 1992} f4 19. Bd4 Ndf6 $19
) 15... Ng4 (15... Bxd6 16. Qxd6 Qxc4 17. Rac1 {maintains some initiative.})
16. Qxg4 Bxd6 17. c5 bxc5 18. bxc5 Nxc5 19. Rac1 {again with light white
initiative, Kovalyov,A (2525)-Suba,M (2487) Benidorm 2008 (½-½, 31)}) 14. g4
{Taking measures against Black's kingside expansion, but without creating
