1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. b3 Nbd7 10. Bb2 Be7 11. e4 O-O 12. Qe3 Qc7 13. Nd4 {This solid and
ambitious system was intensively advocated by Uhlmann. However, his wins were
alternating with losses showing that the position remains rich in content for
both sides.} Rfe8 {Preparing to regroup with ...Bf8 and ...g7-g6.} 14. Rfe1 (
14. h3 $5 Bf8 15. Rae1 Nc5 16. Kh2 Rad8 $1 17. Re2 $5 g6 18. Nc2 {Preparing
f2-f4 without running into ...e6-e5, but removing the knight from the center
offers Black additional ideas.} ({The neutral} 18. Rfe1 $5 {may have been
better.}) 18... Bg7 {Black suddenly threatens ...Nfe4! using the long diagonal
weakening caused by the previous move.} 19. Ba1 {Both sides have carried out
thorough regrouping, but Black's coordination is more effective. The f1-rook
is not playing yet and the dark-squared bishop went back on an unnatural
square in order to avoid tactical tricks based on ...Nxe4. Black cannot
improve his piece position anymore which makes the next move not only logical
but also a necessity.} d5 $1 20. e5 Nfd7 21. cxd5 {The crucial move order.} ({
If} 21. f4 dxc4 $15 {White is left with weaknesses.}) 21... Nxe5 22. f4 {
White must have put big hopes in this move. It seems that Black simply loses
material. But his perfect coordination also implies a high dynamic potential,
allowing the following small combination:} exd5 $1 $15 {A nasty trick based on
Black's superior coordination.} 23. fxe5 d4 $1 24. Nxd4 Rxe5 25. Qf2 Nd3 $1 {
with strong initiative. Uhlmann,W (2555)-Gheorghiu,F (2540) Manila 1976 (0-1,
43) is analyzed in one of the strategic articles.}) (14. Kh1 Bf8 15. f4 g6 16.
Rae1 Bg7 17. h3 Rad8 18. g4 (18. e5 $2 dxe5 19. fxe5 Bxg2+ 20. Kxg2 Qxe5 $1 {
Suba}) (18. Nc2 b5 $132) {So far Uhlmann,W (2530)-Suba,M (2435) Bucharest 1979
(0-1, 48) The best form to start the counterplay in the centre would have been}
18... Nc5 ({The solid} 18... h6 $5 {[%cal Ge6e5] is also possible.}) 19. Ba1 (
19. e5 dxe5 20. fxe5 Nfd7 $17) (19. Rd1 e5 20. fxe5 Rxe5 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. cxd5
Rde8) 19... e5 20. Nde2 (20. fxe5 dxe5 21. Nc2 Rd3) 20... exf4 (20... Ncxe4 21.
Nxe4 Nxe4 22. Bxe4 exf4 23. Rxf4 g5 24. Qf3 Bxa1 25. Bxb7 gxf4 26. Rxa1 $13)
21. Nxf4 Qd7 $11 {planing ...b5.}) 14... Bf8 15. h3 {For unknown to me reasons,
this move is frequently played at an early stage. I do not find problems for
White connected with ...Ng4 at this height of the game.} (15. Rad1 g6 ({
For instance if} 15... d5 $2 16. e5 Ng4 17. Qf4 Ngxe5 18. cxd5 $16) 16. Qd2
Rad8 17. Re2 Qb8 18. Qe1 Nc5 (18... e5 $6 {allowed White's knight to embark on
a favourable path:} 19. Nc2 b5 20. cxb5 axb5 21. Nb4 $16 {Uhlmann,W (2515)
-Ftacnik,L (2550) Debrecen 1989 (0-1, 72)}) 19. Nc2 Bg7 20. Ba1 h5) (15. Re2
Rad8 16. Qd2 Qb8 17. Rae1 g6 ({Or else} 17... Ba8 18. Qd1 g6 19. Qa1 {Nikolic,
P (2515)-Cebalo,M (2510) Banja Luka 1981 (0-1, 54) It is hard to see the point
behind the queen manoeuvre and Black should simply continue his initial plan
with} Bg7 $11) 18. Kh1 $6 Qa8 19. Ba1 Bg7 20. Qd1 Nc5 21. Bb2 {Timoscenko,G 
(2530)-Psakhis,L (2535) Krasnoyarsk 1980 (½-½, 27)} e5 22. Nf3 ({
Unfortunately the exposed king turns} 22. Nc2 $2 {into a mistake:} Ncxe4 23.
Nxe4 Nxe4 24. Bxe4 Bxe4+ 25. Rxe4 f5 $17) 22... b5 $11 {With the knight
passive on e4 Black has worthy counterplay.}) 15... Rad8 16. Rad1 g6 17. Ba1 ({
Another modern game went} 17. Qd2 Bg7 18. Nc2 Nc5 19. Ba1 h5 20. Nb4 Qc8 21.
Qf4 Qa8 22. Nd3 Nfd7 23. Nxc5 {½-½ Kramnik,V (2740)-Shirov,A (2690) Dos
Hermanas 1997}) 17... Qb8 18. Qd2 Bg7 19. g4 Nc5 20. Qc2 {Karjakin,S (2760)
-Ivanchuk, V (2729) Medias 2017 (0-1, 53) Black has no problems whatsoever,
but if he wants to play ...e6-e5 as he did in the game later, now would be the
right moment:} e5 $5 21. Nde2 {The c2-square is not available.} b5 22. cxb5
axb5 23. b4 Ne6 $132 24. Nxb5 d5 25. exd5 Bxd5 26. a4 Bxg2 27. Kxg2 Ng5 $17 *

