{White managed to put a lot of pressure on the d6-pawn. How can Black
neutralize it?} 1... Ne8 $1 {Typical move in such positions. It turns out that
the active position of White's pieces is temporary.} 2. b3 {White is planning
to follow with Ba3.} Ra7 $1 {Another typical way to regroup for this line.
With bishops on board this would have been more complicated to achieve. The
rook is heading for d7 in order to over defend d6.} 3. Ba3 Rd7 {The d6-pawn is
securely protected and Black is planning to expand on the kingside by means of
f7-f5.} *

